Update: After hearing feedback from several other birders, it seems clear that this bird is a Red-naped X Red-breasted Sapsucker.  Continuing since this morning in the same berry tree above Phillip's loop trail. Thanks Jim!  The bird's preferred tree actually appears to be a berry tree growing with a bay tree, creating some confusion. It has sapsucker wells in it which should help identify it.  The bird's plumage is pretty messy and I'm not sure of its identification. It clearly has a strong black and white facial pattern and a black bib, so it's not a pure Red-breasted Sapsucker. But the red crown and nape are extensive and blend with only a hint of black separating them, and there's a bit of red wash below the black bib. The red throat also appears to have a faint black outline all the way around it, which is a strike against pure Red-naped Sapsucker. Perhaps it's a Red-naped X Red-breasted hybrid? Or maybe it's just a juvenile male Red-naped molting into adult plumage and therefore looking a little scruffy. I'd love to hear thoughts from other folks.

Continuing along Alameda Creek trail, found by Derek and Jim yesterday. Small sparrow with clean gray nape and plain breast.  Update from 9/18: After hearing from others and examining my photos more closely, I'm changing this id to Brewer's Sparrow. The bird's markings are very dull, it lacks a pale median crown stripe, its supercilium is grayish with some streaking, and lateral throat stripe is weak.  It looks like this is a different bird than the one Derek photographed, and was apparently in a different part of the trail. But Derek and Jim saw at least two Spizella sparrows, so it's possible that they saw this bird as well.

Observation Details: Continuing bird first found by Jerry Ting. Missing when I first arrived, but settled in very near the path after a Northern Harrier flushed the shorebird flock around 5pm, apparently in the same location it has been seen the previous few days.  Large shorebird very similar to the many nearby Marbled Godwits, but drabber, with much less orange color, plain white belly, and mostly unpatterned back. More prominent supercilium than most Marbleds. Black and white striped tail coverts. Hint of streaked underwing pattern caught in one photo of the bird preening.

Locality: Diablo Foothills Regional Park/Castle Rock Park
Observation Details: Continuing large Zonotrichia sparrow with a pink bill and black bib associating with Golden-crowned sparrows. It flushed and moved into a tree at the southern tip of the field, where it stayed until I left around 9:05am. I didn't see it again when I returned after hiking despite lots of effort looking with a few other birders.

In the field I was convinced that the pictured bird was the continuing Ruff because it is strikingly gray compared to the other roosting Dowitchers and it has sloppy scapulars with a scaly appearance. I never saw its bill. Now I think it's probably a Dowitcher that's late in transitioning to breeding plumage, especially because of its white supercilium, just barely visible barred rump, and similar size to the birds near it. I welcome feedback on the identification. Either way the bird was along the southern edge of the northern pond, visible from the 15mph sign.

Media notes: This photo shows the roosting location as seen from the second lookout spot. The gannet was not visible from anywhere lower along the trail.
Observation Details: Large white seabird with orange head, long pale bill, and black wingtips. I was watching egg rock hoping the gannet would return to roost and was about to give up when I noticed it flying near the cliffs southeast of egg rock around 5:30pm. It landed after circling a few times and was only just visible from the second lookout with benches.

Media notes: The tanager appears to live up to the species' reputation by having a taste for bees.
Observation Details: Seen twice, once around 9:20 in oaks just below the third switchback (the one with a rope swing) and once around 12:30 high in eucalyptus trees between the first and second switchback. Was silent during my first viewing but called a few times during my second.

Continuing bird seen well but briefly in the same area described previously, around 37.909413, -122.331101. Shortly before 1pm one other birder and I saw flashes of an orange face and white stripes down the back. At around 1pm there was a brief but intense downpour which drove away two of the three other birders present. After the rain stopped, the Nelson's Sparrow popped up for nice views of the orange face, gray nape, and white stripes along its back. I'm hoping that the other birder present at this time will post better photos; I only got this single terrible one which shows the orange supercilium, malar, and breast and gray median crown stripe. The bird went down and afterwards we only saw movement as it occasionally darted from one shrub to another.

Not totally sure this was the Greater Pewee, but not sure what else it could be. Seen in bad light at the top of a deciduous tree around (34.0449609, -118.5119538) right before I left. Upright posture, pointed crest, and notched tail noted. I moved to get a better view, but when I looked back the bird was gone and a Cooper's hawk was in the tree :( I never heard the bird make a noise. Not sure these photos are good enough to confirm id but hoping for feedback.
